      <bioghist id="aspace_c536bfe7765228c8344c82419baecbe8">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Lewis B. Cullman is a New York City businessman and philanthropist. Born in 1919, Cullman received a BA from Yale and a master's degree in meteorology from New York University. In his business career, Cullman served as the chief executive of the At-A-Glance calendar and appointment-book company, and in 1964 engineered the purchase of the Orkin Exterminating Company. After selling his company in 1999, Cullman became a philanthropist. He serves on the boards of the New York Public Library, the Museum of Modern Art, and the New York Botanical Garden. He is also involved with Chess in the Schools, a program which teaches chess to New York Public School students, and is the founder of the Cullman Child Development Center, in Sidney, NY. Cullman was thrice married, most recently in 2010 to Louise Hirschfeld. His second wife, Dorothy, played a large role in his philanthropic activites.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <arrangement id="aspace_a63fe9151f1767e79f5f5d31f3cf5da7">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The papers are arranged in three groupings: Business records, Personal papers,  and Photographs.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_d29401182c5d056fbcac8caa4a0c3f58">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection documents the business and philanthropic activities of Lewis B. Cullman. Business records include business dealings with the Allied Graphic Arts Company and Cullman's leveraged buyout of the Orkin Exterminating Company in the 1960s. Also included are two bound volumes documenting the merger of Cullman's company, Cullman Ventures, Inc., with Mead Acquisition Corporation in 1999. Personal papers include biographical information, documents relating to Cullman's relationship with Yale University, records of his philanthropic contributions to New York institutions, and publicity materials for organizations which Cullman founded or contributed to. The collection also includes audiovisual recordings documenting programs funded by Cullman, interviews, and publicity materials about Cullman and his charitable contributions. There are also photographs of Cullman taken at organizations and events related to his philanthropy.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_0d3d50c3d231bdfb6bcbcc7deca8bd24">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>
         <p>Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy of non-commercially produced items for their personal use should consult the ordering reproductions information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.</p>
         <p>Original born digital files, as well as preservation masters, may not be accessed due to their fragility. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist request that they be made. Born digital files cannot be accessed remotely. System requirements include a Manuscripts and Archives computer and file viewing software.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
